'''John Norman Abell''' (18 September 1931 – 25 May 2004) was an English [[cricket]]er active in the 1950s. Born at [[Chelsfield]], [[Kent]], Abell was the son of the cricketer [[George Abell (civil servant)|George Abell]]. He attended [[Marlborough College]], before undertaking studies at [[Worcester College, Oxford]]. While at Oxford he played three [[first-class cricket]] matches for [[Oxford University Cricket Club|Oxford University]], playing twice in 1952 against the [[Free Foresters Cricket Club|Free Foresters]] and [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]], and once in 1953 against [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/27/27393/First-Class_Matches.html|title=First-Class Matches played by John Abell|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> A right-handed [[batsman (cricket)|batsman]] and [[wicket-keeper]], Abell scored 56 runs in his three matches, top-scoring 25, while behind the [[stumps]] he took two [[catch (cricket)|catches]] and made six [[stumping]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/27/27393/f_Batting_by_Team.html|title=First-class Batting and Fielding For Each Team by John Abell|publisher=CricketArchive|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> He notably stumped both Richardson brothers ([[Dick Richardson (cricketer)|Dick]] and [[Peter Richardson (cricketer)|Peter]]) against Worcestershire.<ref name="OBIT">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wisdenalmanack/content/story/156029.html|title=Obituaries index: A-E|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=27 April 2014}}</ref> Unlike his father, Abell did not manage to win a cricketing [[Blue (Oxbridge)|blue]].<ref name="OBIT"/>

He died at [[Marlborough, Wiltshire|Marlborough]], [[Wiltshire]] on 25 May 2004. His brother [[Timothy Abell]] and great-uncle [[Ted Sale]] both played first-class cricket.

